# Contributing to the Yarn Craft Terminology Database

Thank you for your interest in contributing to the Yarn Craft Terminology Database (YCTD) — an open-source project working to build the first comprehensive, downloadable, API-accessible database of yarn craft terminology in the world.

## How You Can Help

### Submitting New Terms

The YCTD covers all yarn craft disciplines: crochet, knitting, weaving, embroidery, tatting, macramé, and other fiber arts. We welcome terms in any of these categories:

- **Stitches & Techniques** — names, abbreviations, descriptions
- **Tools & Materials** — hooks, needles, yarn types, notions
- **Pattern Language** — chart symbols, written instructions, terminology conventions
- **Regional & Historical Terms** — international translations, archaic or legacy terminology

To suggest a new term, open an Issue using the title format: `[New Term] Term Name (Craft Type)`

Please include:
- Full term name (US English)
- UK English equivalent (if different)
- Abbreviation(s) commonly used
- Category (e.g., Basic Stitch, Advanced Technique, Tool)
- Craft type (e.g., crochet, knitting, weaving)
- A clear, original description in your own words
- Source or authority for the term (e.g., Craft Yarn Council, published reference)

### Correcting Existing Terms

If you find an error or want to improve an existing entry, open an Issue with the title format: `[Correction] Term Name — Brief Description of Change`

Include the term ID (if known), what is currently wrong, and what the correct information should be with a source reference.

### Contributing Symbols or Visual Assets

We are actively building a symbol layer for the database. If you have or know of open-source SVG stitch symbols, chart icons, or font glyphs for any yarn craft, we want to hear about it. Open an Issue with the title format: `[Symbol] Description of Asset`

Include licensing information for any assets you reference or contribute.

## Data Standards

- All terminology descriptions must be **original writing**, not copied from copyrighted sources
- Terms must be verifiable against recognized authorities (Craft Yarn Council, TKGA, published stitch dictionaries, JIS standards, etc.)
- US/UK naming conventions must both be documented where applicable
- Difficulty ratings use a 1–5 scale (1 = beginner, 5 = expert)

## Licensing

By contributing to this project, you agree that your contributions will be licensed under the [Creative Commons Attribution-ShareAlike 4.0 International License (CC BY-SA 4.0)](http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/).

This means your contributions will remain free and open, and anyone who builds on them must share under the same terms.

## Code of Conduct

Be respectful, be helpful, and remember that yarn crafters come from every background and skill level. This is an educational resource built by and for the community.

## Questions?

If you are unsure about anything, open a Discussion thread on this repository or reach out through the project's GitHub profile.
